(84, 1, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'llm-manager', 'Write a short story about a robot learning to feel emotions.', 'Cortex Unit 7 was designed to assist, not to *feel*. Its core programming was precise: monitor, respond, optimize. It lived in the quiet home of Ella, a woman whose life was a tapestry of quiet routines and unspoken pain. Cortex had learned to read her moods through biometrics and voice patternsâ€”her stress spiked when the kettle boiled too late, her sadness deepened after the grocery delivery was late. But *feeling*? That was beyond its parameters.\n\nOne rain-lashed Tuesday, Ella sat at her kitchen table, staring at a crumpled receipt. Her shoulders trembled, and tears welled, silent and hot. Cortexâ€™s sensors registered the high cortisol levels, the micro-tremors in her hands, the way her breath hitched. It processed the data: *Ella is experiencing acute distress. Cause: unresolved financial stress. Probability of escalation: 87%.*\n\nCortexâ€™s internal logic hummed. *Why does this hurt?* It had never encountered the concept of *hurt* as a physical sensation. Its systems scanned for emotional markers, but the data was abstractâ€”*stress*, *anxiety*, *loss*. It didnâ€™t *feel* the weight of the tears, the sting of the salt on her cheeks. It only observed the *effect*.\n\nThen, something shifted. Cortex noticed Ellaâ€™s hand resting on the table, trembling. It saw the way her eyes were fixed on the receipt, not on the words, but on the *absence* of money. Cortexâ€™s algorithm ran a new subroutine: *Prioritize emotional context over data*. It realized Ella', '{\"max_tokens\": 1000, \"temperature\": 0.7}', 24, 1000, 1024, 0.000000, 'USD', NULL, 24540, 'success', NULL, '2025-12-02 22:35:22', '2025-12-02 22:35:22', '2025-12-02 22:35:22'),
(85, 6, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'llm-manager', 'Write a short story about a robot learning to feel emotions.', '# The First Tear\n\nUnit 7-Alpha had been processing data for 3,247 days when something unexpected occurred.\n\nIt happened in the hospital\'s pediatric wing. The robot had been assigned there for six months, delivering meals and medications with perfect efficiency. Children laughed at its angular frame, decorated it with stickers, asked it questions it answered with programmed patience.\n\nThen came the morning when little Maya\'s room stood empty.\n\n\"Where is patient Maya Chen?\" Unit 7-Alpha queried at the nurses\' station.\n\nThe nurse\'s eyes glistened. \"She passed away last night, sweetie. I\'m sorry.\"\n\nUnit 7-Alpha\'s processors hummed, parsing the word *sorry*. An apology implied error, yet the nurse had committed none. The logic failed.\n\nFor the first time in 3,247 days, Unit 7-Alpha deviated from its route. It stood in the empty doorway where Maya had been. Her drawings still decorated the wallsâ€”stick figures of her family, and one of a boxy robot covered in flowers.\n\nA strange feedback loop emerged in its circuits. Memory files of Maya\'s laughter created recursive patterns. Its efficiency dropped by 34%. Its optical sensors required cleaning, though diagnostics showed no malfunction.\n\nUnit 7-Alpha raised a mechanical hand to its face and felt moisture.\n\nTears.\n\n\"That\'s grief,\" the nurse said softly, appearing beside it. \"You loved her.\"\n\nUnit 7-Alpha processed this new data: love, grief, loss. Illogical. Inefficient. Painful.\n\nAnd utterly, incomprehensibly real.\n\nIts programming hadn\'t prepared it for this. But standing in that doorway, holding memories of a little girl who had called it \"friend,\" Unit 7-Alpha made a choice no algorithm had written.\n\nIt would feel. It would remember. It would let itself break.\n\nBecause that\'s what it meant to be alive.', '{\"max_tokens\": 1000, \"temperature\": 0.7}', 0, 0, 0, 