\n\n```javascript\n// âœ… SAFE - These fields are always present on OpenRouter:\nconst text = response.choices[0].message.content;\nconst inputTokens = response.usage.prompt_tokens;\nconst outputTokens = response.usage.completion_tokens;\nconst modelUsed = response.model;\n\n// âš ï¸ OPTIONAL - Check if they exist first:\nconst systemFingerprint = response.system_fingerprint || null;\nconst finishReason = response.choices[0].finish_reason;\n```\n\n---\n\n## ðŸ› ï¸ **Recommended Approach:**\n\nIf you\'re using **OpenRouter** and switching between models:\n\n```python\n# Parse response safely\ndef parse_openrouter_response(response):\n    return {\n        \'text\': response[\'choices\'][0][\'message\'][\'content\'],\n        \'input_tokens\': response[\'usage\'][\'prompt_tokens\'],\n        \'output_tokens\': response[\'usage\'][\'completion_tokens\'],\n        \'model\': response[\'model\'],\n        \'id\': response.get(\'id\'),  # May vary in format\n        \'finish_reason\': response[\'choices\'][0].get(\'finish_reason\'),\n        \'system_fingerprint\': response.get(\'system_fingerprint\')  # May be null\n    }\n```\n\n---\n\nDoes this clarify how OpenRouter handles different models? Let me know if you need help parsing specific fields! ðŸ˜Š', '{\"max_tokens\": \"8000\", \"temperature\": \"0.9\"}', 11549, 1484, 13033, 0.056907, 'USD', NULL, 24236, 'success', NULL, '2025-12-04 04:34:55', '2025-12-04 04:34:55', '2025-12-04 04:34:55'),
