(153, 2, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'llm-manager', 'I would need a example with some code.', 'Sure, here is an example of how you might set up unit tests for a simple chat application using Python and the `unittest` module in Python. \n\nLet\'s assume you have a function that creates a new message:\n\n```python\ndef create_message(username, message):\n    return {\n        \'user\': username,\n        \'text\': message\n    }\n```\n\nYou could write unit tests for this function like so:\n\n```python\nimport unittest\nfrom chat import create_message  # assuming your chat module is named \"chat\"\n\nclass TestChat(unittest.TestCase):\n\n    def test_create_message(self):\n        username = \'testuser\'\n        message = \'Hello, world!\'\n        result = create_message(username, message)\n        \n        expected = {\n            \'user\': username,\n            \'text\': message\n        }\n        \n        self.assertEqual(result, expected)  # assert that the function returns a dictionary with correct keys and values\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    unittest.main()\n```\n\nTo run these tests, save them to a file (e.g., `test_chat.py`), then in your terminal you would type:\n\n```shell\npython test_chat.py\n```\n\nThis will execute the unit tests and display any failures or errors in the console.\n', '{\"max_tokens\": \"8000\", \"temperature\": \"0.7\"}', 204, 315, 519, 0.000000, 'USD', NULL, 17470, 'success', NULL, '2025-12-04 20:01:56', '2025-12-04 20:01:56', '2025-12-04 20:01:56'),
