(187, 1, 1, 38, 315, NULL, 'llm-manager', 'I\'m doing: Request/response visualization\nI\'ve already done the response visualization...', 'Ah, great catch â€” you\'ve already got the **response visualization** working! Thatâ€™s awesome. Since youâ€™re focused on **request/response visualization** (with responses already done), Iâ€™ll give you **exactly what you need next**: a *minimal, production-ready* way to log **incoming API requests** in real-time **without breaking your existing flow**.  \n\nHereâ€™s what to do:  \n\n### ðŸ”§ Your Solution (React Code Snippet)\nAdd this **single component** to your debug console â€” itâ€™ll automatically log *every request* your chat sends (like the raw `POST /chat` payload) **as it happens**, while keeping your response visualization intact:\n\n```jsx\n// DebugConsole.jsx (updated version)\nimport { useState, useEffect } from \'react\';\n\nexport default function DebugConsole({ onMessageSent }) {\n  const [messages, setMessages] = useState([]);\n  const [requestLogs, setRequestLogs] = useState([]);\n\n  // ðŸ‘‰ Log EVERY request (when chat sends a message)\n  useEffect(() => {\n    const logRequest = (request) => {\n      setRequestLogs(prev => [...prev, {\n        type: \'request\',\n        timestamp: new Date().toISOString(),\n        method: request.method,\n        url: request.url,\n        payload: request.payload // Your actual message/text\n      }]);\n    };\n\n    // This runs when the user sends a message (your existing flow)\n    onMessageSent?.((request) => {\n      logRequest(request); // ðŸ‘ˆ Critical: Log the request payload HERE\n    });\n\n    return () => {\n      // Cleanup if needed (optional)\n    };\n  }, [onMessageSent]);\n\n  // ðŸ‘‰ Display both requests AND responses (your existing responses + new requests)\n  return (\n    <div className=\"debug-console\">\n      {/* Request logs (new section) */}\n      <h3>ðŸ” API Requests</h3>\n      {requestLogs.map((req, i) => (\n        <div key={i} classNam